Mixed life expectancy changes.

Kranczer S.

Life expectancy for the U.S. total population was essentially unchanged in 1995 
from the prior year. However, analysis by sex reveals that males experienced 
longevity enhancements across the age spectrum. In fact, average remaining 
future lifetime for men established new record highs or remained at peak levels 
at every age. In 1995 expectation of life at birth was 75.7 years for the total 
population, 72.4 years for boys and 78.8 years for girls. At individual ages, 
women's average remaining lifetime has hardly changed since 1990, whereas men 
under age 75 have gained around 0.5 years between 1990 and 1995. In 1995 the 
infant mortality rate established another all-time low, namely 7.6 per 1,000 
live births; this marks the 33rd consecutive year of annual declines.

